            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Dr. Simone Adebayo Wong\u2019s life is a study in purposeful integration. Born in Oakland to a Nigerian immigrant father, a stern but brilliant engineering professor, and a second-generation Chinese American mother, a compassionate social worker, Simone\u2019s upbringing was a crucible of intellectual rigor and human empathy. Dinner table conversations oscillated between systemic logic and individual emotional needs, unknowingly preparing her for a career spent navigating the intersection of both.\n\nShe pursued her undergraduate degree at UC Berkeley before earning her doctorate in Organizational Psychology from NYU. Initially on an academic track, a key turning point came during a brief stint at a floundering tech startup in the late 90s. She was horrified by the brilliant minds being crushed by toxic leadership and broken processes. She saw the human wreckage of burnout firsthand and pivoted, determined to fix cultures from the inside. She returned to the Bay Area and, after years at a large firm, founded her own boutique consultancy, \"Nexus Leadership,\" ten years ago.\n\nSimone\u2019s life is anchored in her Hayes Valley condo. Her 1.2-mile walk to her Financial District office is a non-negotiable ritual. It\u2019s her time to process, observe, and disconnect before diving into the high-stakes psyches of CEOs and VPs. She lost her husband, a gifted software architect named David Wong, to a sudden heart attack nearly a decade ago\u2014a tragedy she quietly attributes to the relentless stress of his industry. This loss fuels her work with a fierce, protective urgency. Her social circle is small but deep, comprised of a few fellow professionals and artists she connects with over gallery openings or quiet dinners in her neighborhood.\n\nNow 51 and at the peak of her profession, Simone\u2019s aspirations have shifted from financial success to legacy. She dreams of writing a book that demystifies compassionate leadership for a new generation. She wants to create a pro-bono mentorship program for women of color entering the tech C-suite, ensuring they have the tools she had to build for herself. For Simone, success is no longer just about optimizing systems; it\u2019s about humanizing them, one executive at a time."
        },
