            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.\nShe remembers being twelve, her father diagramming a city\u2019s water system on a napkin, all elegant logic. Her mother interrupted, speaking of a family whose pipes had burst, describing their quiet desperation. Simone felt a jolt\u2014the cold schematic snapping into focus as a human story. It wasn\u2019t a conflict, she realized, but two halves of a whole truth. That evening planted the seed of her entire worldview: that no system could be understood without first understanding the people within it.\n\n2.\nIt was 2 a.m. in the SOMA warehouse office in 1999. She found the lead programmer, a gentle soul who loved poetry, asleep at his keyboard, drool dotting his copy of Rilke. He\u2019d been there for 36 hours. The sight filled her not with frustration, but with a cold, righteous anger. This wasn\u2019t innovation; it was a human sacrifice to a faulty system. In that fluorescent hum, her academic theories collapsed into a single, urgent mission: she had to fix this. To save the poets.\n\n3.\nJust before he died, she found David asleep on their couch, his laptop still warm on his chest. Instead of waking him for bed, she simply draped a blanket over him, tracing the worried line between his eyebrows, a permanent fixture from endless product cycles. She\u2019d felt a surge of protective love then, but now, a decade later, that memory is a source of profound regret. She hadn\u2019t saved him from the machine. That quiet failure is the engine that drives her, the ghost in her every consultation.\n\n4.\nTen years ago, a month after David\u2019s funeral, she stood alone in the empty FiDi office she\u2019d just leased. The smell of fresh paint and her echoing footsteps were terrifying. She touched the cool glass of the window, seeing not an empire to conquer, but a landscape of people to heal. Founding Nexus Leadership wasn't a business move; it was a vow. It was how she would make his unseen labor\u2014and his loss\u2014mean something more. It was her defiant answer to his silence.\n\n5.\nLast year, over coffee in Hayes Valley, a young VP she\u2019d been mentoring teared up. \u201cThey listened,\u201d she\u2019d said. \u201cI used your framework to talk about the team\u2019s burnout, and they actually listened.\u201d For Simone, it wasn\u2019t a moment of pride, but of profound relief. It felt like watching a seed she\u2019d planted long ago finally sprout in someone else\u2019s garden, vibrant and strong. This, she realized, was the beginning of her true legacy\u2014not just fixing systems, but teaching others how to heal their own worlds."
